      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, hidden soil pests or organisms could definitely be the culprits, and this is where things get really tricky. While most common nutrient thieves are fungi or bacteria, you could be dealing with subterranean pests like certain nematodes that attack root systems. These microscopic pests can effectively \"steal\" the nutrients, making it look like the plant is deficient even if the soil is rich. If you see any signs of stunted growth or wilting that seems disproportionate to the visible leaf issues, a soil sample sent to a lab for microscopic analysis might be necessary.",
